    <fr:title text="Covariant and Contravariant Vectors">Covariant and Contravariant Vectors</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Consider how a <fr:link href="/forest/0006/" title="Basis Transformations on Vector Spaces" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0006/" display-uri="0006" type="local">linear transformation</fr:link> between basis vectors affects an arbitrary vector,</html:p>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[w=B^\nu  f_\nu =B^\nu \Lambda _\nu {}^\mu  e_\mu \implies  A^\mu =B^\nu \Lambda _\nu {}^\mu ]]></fr:tex>
    <html:p>We can also consider the inverse transformation,</html:p>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[e_\mu =(\Lambda ^{-1})_\mu {}^\nu  f_\nu ]]></fr:tex>
    <html:p>leading to</html:p>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[B^\mu =(\Lambda ^{-1})_\nu {}^\mu  A^\nu ]]></fr:tex>
    <html:p>Since the basis vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_\nu ]]></fr:tex> transform <html:em>covariantly</html:em>, we call them <html:strong>covariant vectors</html:strong>. On the other hand, since the coefficients <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B^\nu ]]></fr:tex> transorm with the inverse matrix, we say they transform <html:em>contravariantly</html:em>.</html:p>
    <html:p>We can extent this same idea to the <fr:link href="/forest/0005/" title="Dual Spaces" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0005/" display-uri="0005" type="local">dual space</fr:link>. We want to transform from the basis <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e^\mu ]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^\nu ]]></fr:tex>. From the above we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e^\mu ]]></fr:tex> will transform contravariantly, so we can write,</html:p>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f^\nu =(\Lambda ^{-1})_\mu {}^\nu  e^\mu ]]></fr:tex>
    <html:p>and for an arbitrary dual vector,</html:p>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[w=C_\nu  e^\nu =D_\nu  f^\nu \implies  D_\nu =\Lambda _\nu {}^\mu  C_\mu ]]></fr:tex>
    <html:p>From this we note that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^\nu ]]></fr:tex> transforms <html:em>contravariantly</html:em>, so they are <html:strong>contravariant vectors</html:strong>. The coefficients <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_\nu ]]></fr:tex> transform covariantly.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
