            <fr:title text="Dual Spaces">Dual Spaces</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Consider that we have defined a real <fr:link href="/forest/0003/" title="Elementary Vector Space" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0003/" display-uri="0003" type="local">vector space</fr:link> of dimension n (here we work in 4 dimensions) and we want a <fr:link href="/forest/0004/" title="How to Make a Map" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0004/" display-uri="0004" type="local">map</fr:link>, but we do not wish to create a second vector space.</html:p><html:p>Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is included in our definition of a real vector space, we can consider mapping from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, without creating anything new.</html:p><html:figure><fr:resource hash="0093ba3e4646beaa2c484d6c74958e93"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/forest/0093ba3e4646beaa2c484d6c74958e93.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
  \begin {tikzpicture}
			\draw  rectangle(2,2);
			\node  at (0.5,0.5) {$e_\mu $};
			\node  at (0.5,1.5) {$V$};
			\draw  (1,0) .. controls (1.25,-0.5) and (1.5, -0.25) .. (1.5,0.5);
			\node [draw] at (1.5,0.5) {$R$};
			\node  at (1.5,1.5) {$4$};
	\end {tikzpicture} 
]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>
<html:p>We consider the set of all possible maps that take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>. We call this set of the dual space and denote it by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}^*]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>The dual space satisfies all of the properties of a vector space, so it is itself also a vector space. Since we did not add anything new to our original vector space, this means that by defining a vector space we automatically get an associated dual space.</html:p><html:figure><fr:resource hash="762ab4c8c06fcefda6ceccb4ba9de9ad"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/forest/762ab4c8c06fcefda6ceccb4ba9de9ad.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
  \begin {tikzpicture}
		\draw  rectangle(2,2);
		\node  at (0.5,0.5) {$e_\mu $};
		\node  at (0.5,1.5) {$V$};
		\node [draw] at (1.5,0.5) {$R$};
		\node  at (1.5,1.5) {$4$};
		\draw  (4,0) rectangle(6,2);
		\node  at (4.5,0.5) {$e^\mu $};
		\node  at (4.5,1.5) {$V^*$};
		\node [draw] at (5.5,0.5) {$R$};
		\node  at (5.5,1.5) {$4$};
		\draw [<->,red] (2,1) -- (4,1);
	\end {tikzpicture}
]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>
<html:p>It is convenient (and arbitrary) to make the choice that the respective basis vectors map to one another as,</html:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\braket {e^\mu ,e_\nu }=\delta ^\mu _\nu ]]></fr:tex><html:p>So that,</html:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\braket {B_\mu  e^\mu , A^\nu  e_\nu }=B_\mu  A^\mu ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter>
